            <tbody>
              <tr><td><code>Tab</code></td><td>Move focus to the text input (or to the next focusable element).</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>Shift + Tab</code></td><td>Move focus to the previous focusable element.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>Escape</code></td><td>Clear the input field (when clear button is enabled) or blur the field.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>Enter</code></td><td>Submit the form (when the input is inside a form element).</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Arrow keys</td><td>Move the text cursor within the input content.</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Screen Reader -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="screen-reader" class="doc-h3">Screen Reader</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Always associate the <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">&lt;label&gt;</code> element with the input using the <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">for</code> attribute matching the input's <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">id</code>.</li>
            <li>Use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-describedby</code> to link helper text and error messages to the input so screen readers announce them.</li>
            <li>Use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-required="true"</code> on required fields to communicate obligation to assistive technologies.</li>
            <li>Prefix and suffix text should be included via <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-label</code> or visible label context so the format is clear (e.g., "Price in dollars").</li>
            <li>The clear button should have an explicit <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-label="Clear input"</code> for screen reader users.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Error Handling -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="error-handling" class="doc-h3">Error Handling</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-invalid="true"</code> on the input element when the field is in the Error state.</li>
            <li>Error messages must be linked via <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-describedby</code> so the error is announced when the input receives focus.</li>
            <li>Use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-live="polite"</code> on error message containers for real-time validation so errors are announced dynamically.</li>
            <li>Do not rely solely on color (red border) to indicate errors. Always pair with a descriptive text message.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- RTL Accessibility -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="rtl-accessibility" class="doc-h3">RTL Accessibility</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Set <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">dir="rtl"</code> on the container or use CSS <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">direction: rtl</code> to ensure proper layout mirroring.</li>
            <li>Ensure tab order remains logical in RTL mode (right-to-left reading order).</li>
            <li>Verify that screen readers announce label and helper text in the correct reading direction.</li>
            <li>All interactive elements (clear button, suffix icons) must remain reachable via keyboard in RTL layouts.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Disabled & Read Only -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="disabled-readonly" class="doc-h3">Disabled &amp; Read Only</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li><strong>Disabled:</strong> Use the native HTML <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">disabled</code> attribute. The input is removed from tab order and cannot receive focus.</li>
            <li><strong>Read Only:</strong> Use the native HTML <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">readonly</code> attribute. The input remains focusable and its value can be copied, but it cannot be edited.</li>
            <li>If a disabled field needs to explain <em>why</em> it is disabled, use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-disabled="true"</code> instead of the native <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">disabled</code> attribute so it remains focusable for tooltip access.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Label Position A11y -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="label-position-a11y" class="doc-h3">Label Position</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Regardless of visual label position (Left or Top), the <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">&lt;label&gt;</code> must always be programmatically associated with its input.</li>
            <li>When the label is visually hidden for design reasons, use <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-label</code> or a visually-hidden label element to maintain screen reader support.</li>
            <li>Label Position = Top may improve readability for screen magnifier users who zoom into narrow viewports.</li>
          </ul>
